# Lets explore some hurricane data!
In exploratory data analysis, some of the first steps are to understand what the data is representing. One way to do this is to examine sub-sections of the data by visualizing it in different ways. Well start by examining sub-sections of the hurricane data by year.
Before we begin, re-load the libraries "dplyr" and "ggplot2".
r library(dplyr)
## ## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats': ## ## filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base': ## ## intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
r library(ggplot2)
## Basic inspection of storms in 1975
Lets focus on those storms recorded in 1975. How do we select them? Computationally, this operation involves a logical condition: year == 1975. This condition means that, from all the available year values, we get those that match 1975. This is done via "dplyr" function filter()
First, lets create a subset storms75 by filtering those rows with year equal to 1975:
r storms75 <- filter(storms, year == 1975) storms75
## # A tibble: 86 13 ## name year month day hour lat long status category wind pressure ## <chr> <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <chr> <ord> <int> <int> ## 1 Amy 1975 6 27 0 27.5 -79 tropical d -1 25 1013 ## 2 Amy 1975 6 27 6 28.5 -79 tropical d -1 25 1013 ## 3 Amy 1975 6 27 12 29.5 -79 tropical d -1 25 1013 ## 4 Amy 1975 6 27 18 30.5 -79 tropical d -1 25 1013 ## 5 Amy 1975 6 28 0 31.5 -78.8 tropical d -1 25 1012 ## 6 Amy 1975 6 28 6 32.4 -78.7 tropical d -1 25 1012 ## 7 Amy 1975 6 28 12 33.3 -78 tropical d -1 25 1011 ## 8 Amy 1975 6 28 18 34 -77 tropical d -1 30 1006 ## 9 Amy 1975 6 29 0 34.4 -75.8 tropical s 0 35 1004 ## 10 Amy 1975 6 29 6 34 -74.8 tropical s 0 40 1002 ## # with 76 more rows, and 2 more variables: ts_diameter <dbl>, ## # hu_diameter <dbl>
Now we have the set of storms that occurred in 1975. We can see that there were hurricanes Amy, Caroline, and Doris (we see you, different flavors of misogyny and racism in historical hurricane name choice). However its not obvious from the output if those three hurricanes were all of that year. Are we missing a B name? Lets find out what were the different hurricanes from that year. In R, we could ask what unique() storms happened in that year like this:
r unique(pull(storms75, name))
## [1] "Amy" "Caroline" "Doris"
From the returned output, we see that there is no missing B name hurricane, its just the three unique storms recorded in 1975.
A similar result can be obtained with distinct(), the difference being the way in which the output is returned, in this case under the format of a tibble:
r distinct(storms75, name)
## # A tibble: 3 1 ## name ## <chr> ## 1 Amy ## 2 Caroline ## 3 Doris
Now that we know there are three storms for 1975, we might be curious to know how many rows (or records) are included for each of the storms. "dplyr" allows us to count the number of rows with a particular name value with count(), passing the name of the table, and then the name of the column for which we want to get the counts or frequencies:
r count(storms75, name)
## # A tibble: 3 2 ## name n ## <chr> <int> ## 1 Amy 30 ## 2 Caroline 33 ## 3 Doris 23

Given that, two ways to start to explore the values of wind through vizualization are to graph it with either a histogram or a boxplot. Those are statistical charts to visualize the distribution (all the different values of) of quantitative variables.
So lets use geom_histogram() and see what we get. We are going to show you a synatx of ggplot() slightly different from the one we used for the barcharts. Carefully review the following code:
r p1=ggplot(data = storms75, aes(x = wind)) + geom_histogram() p1
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
r #Same result p2=ggplot(data = storms75) + geom_histogram(aes(x = wind)) p2
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
You should notice now that aes() is an argument of ggplot(), and not anymore an argument of the geometric-object function geom_histogram(). While this may be a bit confusing when learning about "ggplot2", it is a very flexible and powerful behavior of aes(). Again, the important part of aes() is to understand that this function allows you to tell ggplot() which variables in your data table are used as visual attributes of the corresponding geometric elements forming the plot.
We can change the default argument binwidth to get another version of the histogram, for example a bin-width of 5 units (i.e.since wind is measured in knots, a bin width of 5 knots):
r ggplot(data = storms75, aes(x = wind)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5)
or a bin-width of 10:
r ggplot(data = storms75, aes(x = wind)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 10)
### Assignment 4. Now, lets reflect on whats going on in each of the histograms. What features about wind speed do you notice with these histograms? (no right or wrong answers, just explain your thinking)
It appears that the number of hurricanes on the the y-axis correspond to the specific wind speeds on the x-axis. The graph shows the number of hurricanes at a given wind speed.There are many more hurricanes with a wind speed of 25 mph as opposed to 100 mph. It also appears that there are no hurricanes reported with wind speeds between 75 and roughly 85 mph.
Changing the bindwidth between the first and second graphs also changes how the data is presented.
5. Whats your first guess about why you see those features in the data? In other words, how do you interpret the figures? (no right or wrong answers, just explain your thinking)
There is only one year of data plotted from 1975, so its possible there is no data points falling in the wind speed range of 75-85 mph just by chance. The ocean and wind currents may also have worked out in a way that caused hurricanes with lower wind speeds as opposed to higher ones.
While ggplot() does what we ask it to do, the displays may not be the most useful, or meaningful. Why? Think what exactly it is they are plotting. In 1975, there are three storms:
r unique(pull(storms75, name))
## [1] "Amy" "Caroline" "Doris"
But the histograms weve created are not differentiating between any of those three storms. Rather, the visualization is just giving us a general view of the wind values, from the low 20s to the high 90s, or to be more precise:
r summary(pull(storms75, wind))
## Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max. ## 20.00 25.00 52.50 50.87 65.00 100.00
However, we dont really know if all three storms have the same minimum wind speed, or the same maximum wind speed. The good news is that we can tell ggplot() to take into account each different storm name. But now lets use boxplots via geom_boxplot(), mapping name to the x-axis, and wind to the y-axis.
r ggplot(data = storms75, aes(x = name, y = wind)) + geom_boxplot()
### Assignment 6. How do you interpret this plot?
The middle line of the box is the median (average), and the bottom edge of the box is the first quartile. The top edge of the box is the third quartile. And the line extending downward leads to a point, which is the minimum. Th line extending outward from the box is the maximum. The two points away from the box plots at the top are outliers.
7. How does the new perspective you gained through this plot change (or not) your answer to question 5? (no right or wrong answers, just explain your thinking)
I think this plot is much clearer on what data for wind speed belongs to which storm, as opposed to the previous plots. It also could give an idea of chronological order. The previous plots for #4 and #5 present data for the storms in 1975 in a messy way, whereas this plot only plots data corresponding to the 3 storms specifically. You can tell average wind speed here as opposed to the other plots.
We can get an alternative plot with density curves thanks to the geom_density() function. The syntax in this case is different. Lets first do it without separating storms, and then we do it taking into account the storm names.
Heres the command that plots a density curve of wind, without distinguishing between storms. Observe also how the argument fill is set to color 'gray':
r ggplot(data = storms75, aes(x = wind)) + geom_density(fill = 'gray')
As you can tell, the density curve looks like the profile of a roller coaster, or like the silhouette of three mountain peaks. Its basically a smoothed-out version of the histograms we made earlier. Is this a pattern followed by wind speed in all storms? Or is it just an artifact due to the fact that we are plotting data without taking into consideration the context of storms75?
Lets replot density of wind, but now distinguishing between each storm. We do this by mapping name to the color argument:
r ggplot(data = storms75, aes(x = wind, color = name)) + geom_density(aes(fill = name))
Aha! Now things look more interesting: the roller coast shape of the first call to geom_density() turned out to be an artificial pattern. As you can tell from the above plot, each storm has its own different density curve.
To get a better visualization, we can take the previous command and add a bit of transparency to the colors, this is done with the argument alpha inside geom_density(). Note how arguments are specified inside geom_density(): we map name to the color-fill attribute of the curve inside aes(), but we set alpha = 0.5 outside aes():
r ggplot(data = storms75, aes(x = wind, color = name)) + geom_density(aes(fill = name), alpha = 0.5)
We are going to take advantage of this graphic to introduce another cool feature of "ggplot2" that allows us to split data based on categorical or discrete variables, in order to produce separated frames called facets. Heres the command previous commandwithout alpha transparencyadding a new layer given by facet_wrap():
r ggplot(data = storms75, aes(x = wind, color = name)) + geom_density(aes(fill = name)) + facet_wrap(~ name)
In this command we are faceting by name, and what this does is to create facets, one for each category of name. In other words, we get separated density curves, one for each storm. The syntax inside facet_wrap() uses the tilde ~ operator which is the formula operator in R. Basically, the command ~ name tells ggplot() to create facets based on the values of name.
### Assignment 8. For your teams year-of-choice from question 1, create a histogram of all hurricane wind speeds.
r ggplot(data = storms96, aes(x = wind, color = name)) + geom_histogram(aes(fill = name)) + facet_wrap(~ name)

Lets keep exploring wind but now lets do it chronologically, that is, graphing the wind values in the order that they were recorded (recall storms are tracked every six hours).

We begin with a scatterplot using geom_point(). We specify that the x-axis should use a numeric sequence from one to the number of rows in amy75 (1:nrow(amy75)). The x-axis represents each sequential time point. On the y-axis, we plot wind:

ggplot(data = amy75, aes(x = 1:nrow(amy75), y = wind)) +
  geom_point()

Hmm, an x-axis titled 1:nrow(amy75) isnt very descriptive to someone who isnt creating this code.

Assignment

  1. Add on another layer to the plot with xlab to re-label the x-axis more descriptively.
ggplot(data = amy75, aes(x = 1:nrow(amy75), y = wind)) +
  geom_point()+ xlab("Six hour timepoints between 06-27-75 and 07-04-75")

Because the x-axis denotes progression over time, viewers can more easily interpret the plot if sequential dots are connected with a line. A simple way to do this is by adding another layer to our plot, this time with geom_line()

ggplot(data = amy75, aes(x = 1:nrow(amy75), y = wind)) +
  geom_point() +  xlab("Six hour timepoints between 06-27-75 and 07-04-75") +
  geom_line()

At this point, we may be interested in incorporating the other types of data we have about Amy. Lets consider status. (You can go back and check the original output to understand what status may be representing)

One option is to map status to the color attribute of points:

ggplot(data = amy75, aes(x = 1:nrow(amy75), y = wind)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = status)) + 
  geom_line()

We see that Amy started as a tropical depression, and then became a tropical storm, but never became a hurricane. For a storm to reach hurricane status, of category 1, it must have one-minute maximum sustained winds of at least 64 kn (33 m/s; 74 mph; 119 km/h).

What about the pressure values of Amy? We can produce a similar scatterplot with a line connecting the dots:

ggplot(data = amy75, aes(x = 1:nrow(amy75), y = pressure)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = status)) + 
  geom_line()

As an exploratory exercise, we can also try representing more aspects of the data together by playing with the size of points, the size (width) of lines, colors, etc. Heres one suggestion graphing pressure and taking into account the wind speed reflected in the size of points and line segments:

ggplot(data = amy75, aes(x = 1:nrow(amy75), y = pressure)) +
  geom_line(aes(size = wind), lineend = "round", color = 'gray70') +
  geom_point(aes(size = wind, color = status))

If you know a little bit about storms, you know theres actually an association between wind and pressure. But lets pretend for a second that we dont know much about tropical storms, hurricanes, and things like that (Rori doesnt have to pretend). By looking at the previous chart, this should allows us to guess that something is going on between the pressure of a storm and its wind speed. As Amy becomes stronger, with higher winds, its pressure levels drop accordingly.
